				<name type="primary" sortindex="1" value="Guardian Angels: The Invisible Battle" />
			
						                           
						               													<description>A Christian board game set in present time. People with their guardian Angels travel through the time of their life (days of the week on the game board), getting ether into a Wisdom square, or into a Battle square, depending on the number rolled on the dice. When they land on a square, they draw a Wisdom or a Battle card and play them out according to the rules.&amp;#10;&amp;#10;The main resource in the game is Grace, which is represented by the colored rubber bands. People are awarded Grace when they draw from the sources of Wisdom and build the Church. They use up Grace when fighting Passions in Battles.&amp;#10;&amp;#10;Wisdom cards contain short stories from the Bible (or other sources), that players are asked to re-tell with their own words. The players are rewarded with Grace, depending on the completeness of the story. After the story telling, they go into building the Church from the puzzle pieces.&amp;#10;&amp;#10;Battle cards describe the life situations the People get into and what the Angles and the Passions advising them to do in these circumstances. Depending on the difficulty of the situation, there are from one to four Passions attacking the Person. Your goal is to help the angles to knock them down by shooting them with the Grace you&amp;rsquo;ve accumulated so far. If you can&amp;rsquo;t shoot down all the Passions, the Person goes into the Sinful Circle &amp;ndash; an inner circle on the game board, where all the squares are Battle squares.&amp;#10;&amp;#10;You&amp;rsquo;ll be building the church out of puzzle pieces on every Wisdom turn and on every successful Battle turn. If a Battle is lost, you don&amp;rsquo;t get to build the Church.&amp;#10;&amp;#10;The game is over, when the Church is built. Everyone wins, but those with the most Grace bands left deserve the biggest praise.&amp;#10;&amp;#10;-description from designer&amp;#10;&amp;#10;</description>
